    title: 'How to Write Resume Bullets That Actually Get Interviews',
    excerpt: 'Most resume bullets bury the lead. Learn the achievement-first formula that makes recruiters stop scrolling.',
    date: 'Apr 18, 2026',
    readTime: '7 min',
    content: [
      { type: 'p', text: 'The average recruiter spends six seconds scanning a resume before deciding whether to read it properly. Six seconds. That means your resume bullets are doing the heaviest lifting of your entire job search — and most people write them completely wrong.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'The Most Common Resume Bullet Mistake' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'Most professionals write their resume bullets like job descriptions: they list responsibilities instead of achievements. "Managed social media accounts." "Led a team of five engineers." "Responsible for client onboarding." These bullets describe what the role existed to do — not what you personally accomplished while in it.' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'The fix is deceptively simple: lead with the result, then explain how you got there.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'The Achievement-First Formula' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'Every strong resume bullet follows the same pattern: [Result] + [Action] + [Context]. This is a deliberate inversion of how most people write. Instead of "Managed a team that increased revenue," you write "Grew revenue 34% by restructuring the sales team\'s territory model."' },
      { type: 'ul', items: [
        'Lead with a number or outcome whenever possible — percentages, dollar amounts, timeframes, or scale',
        'Use a strong action verb that describes your specific contribution, not the team\'s general activity',
        'Add context that explains why the result was hard to achieve or significant in scope',
        'Keep it to one line — two at most — and never use complete sentences',
      ]},
      { type: 'h2', text: 'Before and After Examples' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'Here is what the transformation looks like in practice across different industries.' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Software Engineering' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'Before: "Worked on backend performance improvements for the payments service."' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'After: "Reduced API response time by 62% by migrating payments service to async processing, cutting customer drop-off at checkout by 18%."' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Marketing' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'Before: "Responsible for email marketing campaigns."' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'After: "Lifted email open rates from 18% to 31% by redesigning subject line strategy and A/B testing cadence across 3M subscriber list."' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Operations' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'Before: "Managed vendor relationships and procurement."' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'After: "Renegotiated contracts with top 8 vendors, saving $240K annually while maintaining service levels across all SLA commitments."' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'What If You Don\'t Have Hard Numbers?' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'Not every role produces clean metrics — and that is fine. You can still write achievement-first bullets by leading with qualitative outcomes: "First to implement X at the company," "Led initiative that was adopted company-wide," or "Reduced recurring complaints about Y." The key is that the bullet describes something that changed because you were there, not something the role was meant to do regardless of who filled it.' },
      { type: 'callout', text: '💡 Tip: Use Brand Syndicate\'s AI generator to automatically rewrite your experience into achievement-framed, ATS-optimized bullets — no spreadsheet required.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'Tailoring Bullets to Each Job' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'One resume does not fit every role. Once you have a strong master list of achievement-first bullets, customize the top three to five for each application by matching the language in the job description. If they use "drove growth," use "drove growth." This is not gaming the system — it is communicating in the language your reader already uses.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'The Bullet Audit' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'Go through every bullet on your current resume and ask two questions: Does this describe a result or a responsibility? And would this bullet be true of anyone who held this role, or specifically of what I accomplished? If you can not answer yes to the second question, rewrite it.' },
    ],
